("FBC"), the parent holding company of Farmers Bank of Lynchburg ("FBL"), acquired 100% of the outstanding stock of Oakland Deposit Bank (Oakland, TN) in a stock exchange. FBC then immediately merged the Oakland bank with FBL in a combination of businesses under common control, with FBL being the survivor.Since SFAS 141-R does not apply to such trans, no purchase accounting adjustments were made to ODB's books, other than to zero out all income stmt accts and all retained earnings accts at the time of merger. Addt'l stock purchased 9-30-09, with new shares issued at the Oakland acquision, has taken the majority shareholders' ownership position to 80%, and therefore purchase accounting has been applied as of that date.

894834	8	0	1	24	CONF	7	0	0	69	32	102	0	0	0	0	0	0	1481	0	0	0	true	26	0	0	0	2	18	52	20	0	0	58	36	38	22	-8	Other			Loan documentation-Repo Fees	Telephone	Other Expenses				Capital Injection into Surplus Account- See Below				Text 4498- In September 2009, outside investors purchased approximately 98% of Robinson Bancshares, Inc ("RBI") for $1,425,802 in cash. September, the investors invested another approximately $2,000 into RBI which was used to pay expenses at the RBI level. The $1,425,802 was flowed from RBI into the Capital Surplus Account at Bank of Lenox. On September 30, when it appeared the Bank of Lenox Capital leverage ratio would be short of 7%, the investors put another $55,000 into "RBI", which was flowed down to the bank. The net effect was an infusion of $1,480,802 into the Capital Surplus account of Bank of Lenox.

This was accounted for as a reorganization using the pooling-of interests method. In March 2007, the Bank received a one time allocation of $8.6 million in overhead.  Effective 4/1/07, the Bank has entered into an agreement with its parent which states that the parent agrees not to allocate any overhead to the Bank until its net income, after allocation, exceeds $2 million for a period of three years. Legg Mason Investment Counsel & Trust Company, NA ("Bank") now assesses and monitors its capital, capital needs and liquidity on a quarterly basis through its Investment Policy Committee. The Income & Expense sheet, Balance Sheet and Tier 1 Capital is reviewed monthly.  The Investment Policy Committee minutes are submitted to the Board of Directors.  In addition, as part of the quarterly financial review, the Bank's capital and liquidity will be reviewed by the Board.

Push-down purchase accounting created a Core Deposit Intangible asset in the amount of $1,120,000.  This intangible asset is amortized in accordance with GAAP and expensed resulting in a significant reduction in the reported earnings of the bank.  The earnings impact for the first 12-month period beginning 9/1/08 was $367,000.  The earnings impact for the second 12-month period beginning 9/1/09 is estimated to be $249,000. Accordingly in order to determine the tangible earnings of the bank, line 7.c.2. of Schedule RI should be added back to the reported net income on line 14 of the same schedule. The implementation of this accounting principal requires the Bank to reclassify that portion of non-credit losses associated with investment securities, recorded through the income statement in 2008, out of beginning retained earnings on January 1, 2009 and into other comprehensive income.
